arch:property.oc:show_val: X21 is a piece of worked antler. This is a fill unit from space 342 in West Mound Trench 5. It is below a sequence of fills (16896, 18309, 18311) which are probably actually stratigraphically a single unit. (18328) itself was recognised by a change in colour from (18311) and was initially thought to represent a trodden surface within the fill. Pottery refits between this unit and (16896) indicate that the depositional sequence spans a short period, however, especially since neither the bone nor the pottery in either unit looks reworked. We are probably talking about brief pauses in deposition within the space rather than any longer-term surfaces. The faunal unit is very similar to that from (16896), if slightly less beautifully preserved. (18309) and (18311) have yet to be assessed. The unit is fairly large for room fill, with perhaps 1600 fragments from around 500 litres. More than 95% of the assemblage is sheep-sized, of which the majority of diagnostic specimens are sheep, with a few goats – some wild. Cattle-sized species make up less than 5% of the scrap and only contribute seven diagnostics (three cattle, one equid, one red deer, two indet.), excluding three pieces of worked antler. There are also a few pieces of hare-sized scrap and a single human metapodials. As in (16896), the sheep sized material is very evenly spread around the body: all parts are represented and neither heads, feet, axial elements, or meaty limb bone elements are underrepresented. Fragmentation is limited, varying little from (16896). The assemblage is characterised by a lot of intact diagnostic zones (~40% of fragments are diagnostic), including some of the most porous elements and even a few complete long bones. As with (16896), the long bone and rib shaft fragments look a little bit closer to a typical room fill, with a modal size of 30-40mm. There are very few indeterminate (i.e. 117) fragments - perhaps 200 - and very few tiny crumbles for a completely sieved unit. **check back after flot** Carnivore action is again extremely limited, with digestion and gnawing both below 5%, plus the presence of a few more-or-less intact proximal humeri, distal femora, etc. Burning is rare, with perhaps 5% of specimens carbonized and only a few calcined. Surface conditions is good, if slightly less so than (16896): most specimens are at stage 3 (‘slight weathering’) but a substantial proportion (10%?) are at stage 2 (‘very slight weathering’), with rather fewer (5%?) at stage 4. Colouration is consistent both within the unit and in comparison to other ffills in the space: most material is a pale yellow colour, although there is slightly more variation in the scrap than amongst diagnostics. The appearance of the material points to a high degree of coherence, and this is confirmed by a large number of articulations, many of which were recognised by the excavators and bagged together, demonstrating that they were definitely in situ. These include unfused epiphyses and carpals/tarsals, but also several groups of vertebrae. While the composition of the assemblage does not suggest a single event, the articulations indicate that final deposition must have taken place before the soft tissues were completely decomposed, and that there was minimal subsequent disturbance. The pottery refits with (16896) are interesting in the light of this, and perhaps suggest that the fill of space 342 was formed through a rapid succession of dumping events, each consisting of fresh material. This unit a priority for study in 2010. No flot as yet. DZ count: Ovis/Capra – 114; Bos – 1.5; Homo – 0.2.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
